The site itself has five pages.  The homepage leads with whatever team is having the worst day, then drops into a leaderboard of the top five chaos programs right now.  Below that is a subscribe section because if your fanbase is spiraling, you probably want to know about it first thing in the morning.  The rankings page shows all 40 programs sorted by chaos score with expandable cards that break out each metric and surface real fan quotes pulled from Reddit.  The team pages go deeper: today's score, a 30-day history chart, and a rolling seven-day strip so you can see whether a fanbase is trending up or cooling off.

There's also a Vault page with a classified document aesthetic that archives each day's scores going back 30 days.  It looks like someone leaked internal government files, except the files are about whether Ohio State fans are panicking.

The tone across the whole site is Barstool-adjacent.  Every team has what I'm calling a Melt Scale, which is a logo progression that literally shows the program's mascot melting as the chaos score climbs.  A Category 1 is clean and normal.  By Category 5, things are falling apart visually.  The Spiral Trigger, the one-sentence explanation of what set fans off, is written to sound like a sportscaster who stopped being professional at some point and never recovered.  Fan quotes get surfaced directly from Reddit so you can see exactly what kind of takes are circulating.  The point is not to be a neutral data dashboard.  The point is to make you laugh at whatever fanbase is having a complete breakdown over a third-quarter turnover in week two of the season.

